Introduction¶

The project is to devise a method to obtain a equilibrium measure $d\mu = w(x) dx$ from a potential $e^{-V(x)}$. To understand what an equilibrium measure is, let us recall the joint density of eigenvalues of $n\times n$ Gaussian Unitary Ensembles (GUE) when all the entries are normally distributed (i.e. $V(x) = x^2/2$): \begin{align*} p_A(\lambda_1,...,\lambda_n) &\propto \prod_{i<j} |\lambda_i - \lambda_j|^2 \exp \left( -\sum_i \frac{\lambda_i^2}{2} \right) \, d^n \lambda \end{align*}

We can scale up by $\lambda = \sqrt{n} x$ (like how we scale the eigenvalues during GUE experiments) to obtain \begin{align*} p_A(x_1,...,x_n) &\propto \prod_{i<j} |x_i - x_j|^2 \exp \left( -n \sum_i \frac{x_i^2}{2} \right)\, d^n x \\ &= \exp \left( -\left(\sum_{i \neq j} \ln |x_i - x_j|^{-1} + n \sum_{i=1}^n V(x_i) \right) \right), \quad V(x) = x^2/2 \end{align*}

Dyson has interpreted the term inside the bracket as the total potential of a gas of $n$ electrons confined on a real axis with position $x_1, x_2, ..., x_n$: \begin{equation*} \sum_{i \neq j} \underbrace{\ln |x_i - x_j|^{-1}}_{\text{potential from repulsion}} + n \sum_{i=1}^n \underbrace{V(x_i)}_{\text{exterior potential}} \end{equation*}

If we define the counting measure $\mu_n$ of scaled position with density (with respect to Lebesgue measure) $w_n(x) = n^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n \delta_{x_i}(x)$, then we can write the above term as $n^2 I^V(\mu_n)$, where $I^V(\mu)$ is a functional of all probability measures in $\mathbb{R}$ defined as \begin{equation} I^V(\mu) = \iint_{t \neq s} \ln |t-s|^{-1} \, \mu(dt) \, \mu(ds) + \int V(s) \, \mu(ds) \end{equation}

We expect that the rescaled positions $x_i$ in the counting measure $\mu_n$ are chosen so that it minimises of $I^V(\mu)$ among all choices of positions $x_i$, and the counting measure $\mu_n$ will converge (weakly) to the global eigenvalue distribution $\mu$ (with density $w(x)$) as $n \to \infty$. Therefore $\mu$ (with density $w(x)$) is a minimiser of $I^V(\mu)$, known as the equilibrium measure of $V(x)$. Remark: we expect $\mu$ to have compact support.

One might wonder how can we experimentally determine $w_n(x)$ (i.e. the rescaled positions). Let's arrange $x_i$ so that it becomes an increasing sequence. We can 'differentiate' the term inside the bracket with respect to $x_i$ to obtain \begin{equation} \frac{2}{n} \sum_{j=1, \, j \neq i}^n \frac{1}{x_i-x_j} - V'(x_i) = 0 \quad (\forall i) \end{equation} (formally we can use Euler Lagrange), which is equivalent to saying \begin{equation} \sum_{j=1, \, j \neq i}^n \frac{2}{\lambda_i-\lambda_j} - V'(\lambda_i) = 0 \quad (\forall i) \end{equation}

We will start with the equilibrium systems to derive the equilibrium measure. Let us be reminded with the standard results of the Cauchy Transforms and Hilbert Transform.

Complex Number Primer¶

Without further specification we write $f$ as a function from $\mathbb{C}$ to $\mathbb{C}$ and a piecewise-$C^1$ curve in $\mathbb{C}$ as $\gamma$. Recall the following definitions.

Definition: (Cauchy Transform) The Cauchy Transform is the operator \begin{equation} \mathcal{C}_\gamma [f](z) = \frac{1}{2\pi i} \int_\gamma \frac{f(x) \, dx}{x-z} \end{equation}

Definition: (Hilbert Transform) The Hilbert Transform is the operator \begin{equation} \mathcal{H}_\gamma [f](z) = \frac{1}{\pi} \text{PV}\int_\gamma \frac{f(x) \, dx}{x-z} \end{equation} where the value of integral is considered as (Cauchy) Principal Value.

The Cauchy Transform comes from the Cauchy Theorem. In the case when $\gamma$ is a closed curve, we have $\mathcal{C}_\gamma [f](z) = f(z)$ whenever $z$ is inside $\gamma$, and $\mathcal{C}_\gamma [f](z) = 0$ whenever $z$ is outside $\gamma$ (the 'inside' and 'outside' regions comes from the definition of Jordan Curve Theorem). When $z$ is on $\gamma$, we have $\mathcal{C}_\gamma [f](z) = f(z)/2$. This comes from a deformation argument. It is clear that there is jump for $\mathcal{C}_\gamma [f](z)$. As a convention we define the following limits at points when $f(z)$ is not defined (e.g. points on branch cuts).

Definition (Left and Right Limits): define the following limits at $z = z_0$ \begin{align*} f^+(z_0) &= \lim_{z \to z_0^+} f(z), \quad \text{limit from the 'left'.} \\ f^-(z_0) &= \lim_{z \to z_0^-} f(z), \quad \text{limit from the 'right'.} \end{align*} Unfortunately the definition of 'left' and 'right' are subtle. Here we consider those limits when $z_0$ is on the curve $\gamma$ where $f(z_0)$ cannot be properly defined:

  • If $\gamma$ is closed then we consider 'left' as region bounded by $\gamma$ and 'right' as the complement of the bounded region.
  • If $\gamma$ is real line / subset of real line we consider 'left' as region above the real axis and 'right' as region below the real axis.
  • Otherwise, we consider 'left' as region to the left of $\gamma$ and 'right' as region to the right of $\gamma$.
For the case when $\gamma$ is closed, we immediately obtain the following formula:

Theorem (Plemelj I): When $z_0 \in \gamma$ we have $$\mathcal{C}^+_\gamma [f](z_0)-\mathcal{C}^-_\gamma [f](z_0)=f(z_0)$$

Of course, one might also think about the additive jump of the Cauchy Transform. Observe when $z_0 \in \gamma$ the following holds: \begin{gather*} \mathcal{C}^+_\gamma [f](z_0) = \frac{1}{2}g(z_0) + \frac{1}{2\pi i} \int_\gamma \frac{g(x)}{x-z_0} \\ \mathcal{C}^-_\gamma [f](z_0) = -\frac{1}{2}g(z_0) + \frac{1}{2\pi i} \int_\gamma \frac{g(x)}{x-z_0} \\ \end{gather*} So we obtain the following formula

Theorem (Plemelj II): When $z_0 \in \gamma$ we have $$\mathcal{C}^+_\gamma [f](z_0)+\mathcal{C}^-_\gamma [f](z_0)=\frac{1}{\pi i} \int_\gamma \frac{g(x)}{x-z_0} = -i\mathcal{H}_\gamma [f](z_0)$$

We go back to our problem. Observe that for all $z \neq x_i$ \begin{equation*} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{j=1}^n \frac{1}{z-x_j} = \int_{-\infty}^\infty \frac{w_n(x)}{z-x} \end{equation*} Moreover, for all $z = x_i$ \begin{equation*} \lim_{\epsilon \to 0} \left( \int_{-\infty}^{x_i - \epsilon} + \int_{x_i - \epsilon}^{\infty} \right) \frac{w_n(x)}{z-x}\, dx = \sum_{j=1, x_j < x_i}^n \frac{1}{z-x_j} + \sum_{j=1, x_j > x_i}^n \frac{1}{z-x_j} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{j=1, \, j \neq i}^n \frac{1}{x_i-x_j} \end{equation*} Therefore for all $z = x_i$, \begin{equation*} -2\pi \mathcal{H}_\gamma [w_n](x_i) - x_i = 0 \iff \mathcal{H}_\gamma [w_n](x_i) = -\frac{V'(x_i)}{2\pi} \end{equation*} If $n \to \infty$, by weak convergence, \begin{equation*} \mathcal{H}_\gamma [w](z) = -\frac{V'(z)}{2\pi} \end{equation*} By Plemenj II, $$(-2i\pi)\mathcal{C}^+_\gamma [w](z)+ (-2i\pi)\mathcal{C}^-_\gamma [w](z) = -\pi \mathcal{H}_\gamma [w](z) = V'(z)$$ Define $\phi(z) = (-2i\pi)\mathcal{C}_\gamma [w](z)$. Then we have $$\phi^+(z)+ \phi^-(z) = V'(z)$$ Moreover, $$\phi^+(z)- \phi^-(z) = (-2i\pi) (\mathcal{C}^+_\gamma [w](z) - \mathcal{C}^-_\gamma [w](z)) = (-2i\pi) w(z)$$ which implies $$w(z) = \frac{i}{2\pi} (\phi^+(z)- \phi^-(z))$$ The main task is to obtain $\phi$. We have shown in simulation that $\mu$ (or $w$) must have compact support, so we have $$\phi^+(z)+ \phi^-(z) = V'(z), \quad z \in \text{supp} \mu$$

Remark: There might be more than one solution. We need to impose further condition: notice that if $w(x)$ is a 'well-behaved' density of probability measure on $\mathbb{R}$ then $w(x)$ integrates to 1. It follows that \begin{align*} \mathcal{C}_\gamma [w](z) &= -\frac{1}{2\pi i} \int_{\text{supp}\, \mu} \frac{w(x) \, dx}{z-x} \\ &= -\frac{1}{2\pi i z} \int_{\text{supp}\, \mu} \frac{w(x) \, dx}{1-(x/z)}\\ &= -\frac{1}{2\pi i z} \int_{\text{supp}\, \mu} w(x) \left(1 + \frac{x}{z} + ... \right)\\ &= -\frac{1}{2\pi i z} + ... \end{align*} (if dominated convergence theorem applies). Therefore we must have $$\phi(z) = \frac{1}{z} + ...$$

The Chebyshev-Joukowsky Map¶

We introduce the Chebyshev-Joukowski Map: \begin{equation} J(z) = \frac{z+z^{-1}}{2} \end{equation}

In [16]:
J(z) = (z + 1/z)/2
Out[16]:
J (generic function with 1 method)

There are a few useful facts for this specific conformal map. Firstly, it maps unit circle $\mathbb{T}$ ($z = e^{i \theta}$) onto a line segment $[-1,1]$ \begin{equation} z = \frac{e^{i\theta}+e^{-i\theta}}{2} = \cos{\theta} \end{equation}

In [17]:
plot([J(exp(im*θ)) for θ in range(0,stop=2*pi,length=100)], yrange=[-1,1], label=false)
Out[17]:

It maps non-unit circles to ellipses surrounding the interval $[-1,1]$: \begin{equation} z = \frac{re^{i\theta}+r^{-1}e^{-i\theta}}{2} = \frac{1}{2} \left(r + \frac{1}{r} \right) \cos \theta + \frac{1}{2} \left(r - \frac{1}{r} \right) \sin \theta, \quad r \neq 0,1 \end{equation}

In [18]:
plot([J(2*exp(im*θ)) for θ in range(0,stop=2*pi,length=100)], yrange=[-1,1], label="r=2")
plot!([J(exp(im*θ)) for θ in range(0,stop=pi,length=100)], yrange=[-1,1], label="r=1")
Out[18]:

Owing to the fact that this map maps unit circle $\mathbb{T}$ to the interval $[-1,1]$, if a function $f(z)$ (e.g. $f(z) = \sqrt{z-1} \sqrt{z+1}$) has jump on interval $[-1,1]$, then the function $J(z)$ will have jump on the unit circle.

In [19]:
pJa = phaseplot(-2..2, -2..2, z -> sqrt(z-1)*sqrt(z+1), xlabel="Re(z)", ylabel="Im(z)", title="phase plot of f(z)");
pJb = phaseplot(-2..2, -2..2, z -> sqrt(J(z)-1)*sqrt(J(z)+1), xlabel="Re(z)", ylabel="Im(z)", title="phase plot of f(J(z))");
plot(pJa, pJb, layout=(1,2), size=(600,300))
Out[19]:

Therefore, if $\phi(z)$ satisfies the equation \begin{equation*} \phi^+(z) - \phi^-(z) = f(z) \end{equation*} then the function $\psi(z):= \phi(J(z))$ satisfies the equation \begin{equation*} \psi^+(z) - \psi^-(z) = f(J(z)) \end{equation*} As we will see, the latter equation is much easier to be solved.

Inverse maps: For $x \notin (-1,1)$, we may define two inverse maps of $J(x)$, namely $J^{-1}_{+}(x)$ and $J^{-1}_{-}(x)$. \begin{gather*} J^{-1}_{+}(x) = x - \sqrt{x-1} \sqrt{x+1} \quad \text{(interior)} \\ J^{-1}_{-}(x) = x + \sqrt{x-1} \sqrt{x+1} \quad \text{(exterior)} \end{gather*}

In [20]:
Jinvp(x) = x - sqrt(complex(x-1))*sqrt(complex(x+1))
Jinvn(x) = x + sqrt(complex(x-1))*sqrt(complex(x+1))
Out[20]:
Jinvn (generic function with 1 method)

The first map maps $x$ to the interior of unit circle, while the second map maps $x$ to the exterior of unit circle.

In [21]:
x = -1+im
plot([exp(im*θ) for θ in range(0,stop=2*pi,length=100)], label="circle")
scatter!([x],label="x")
scatter!([Jinvp(x)],label="J₊⁻¹(x)")
scatter!([Jinvn(x)],label="J₋⁻¹(x)")
Out[21]:

Notice that $J^{-1}_{+}(x) = (J^{-1}_{-}(x))^{-1}$. Moreover, both maps have jump along the interval $[-1,1]$

In [22]:
x = 2+3im
isapprox(Jinvp(x),1/(Jinvn(x)))
Out[22]:
true

We can also define inverse map for $x \notin (-\infty,-1] \cup [1,\infty)$, namely \begin{gather*} J^{-1}_U(x) = x + i\sqrt{1-x} \sqrt{x+1} \quad \text{(upper)} \\ J^{-1}_D(x) = x - i\sqrt{1-x} \sqrt{x+1} \quad \text{(lower)} \end{gather*}

In [23]:
Jinvu(x) = x + im*sqrt(complex(1-x))*sqrt(complex(x+1))

The first map maps $[-1,1]$ to the upper half of unit circle, while the second map maps $[-1,1]$ to the lower half of unit circle.

A Canonical Example¶

We go back to the example $V(x) = x^2/2$, or $V'(x) = x$. Let's assume the equilibrium measure (or the density $w(x)$) has support $[-b,b]$ with $b > 0$. (The support must be symmetric since $V(x)$ is symmetric.) By rescaling $x \to bx$ we are solving the equation \begin{equation} \phi^+(x) + \phi^-(x) = bx, \quad x \in [-1,1] \end{equation} Writing $\psi(z) = \phi(J(z))$ we have \begin{equation} \psi^+(z) + \psi^-(z) = \frac{b}{2}\left(z + \frac{1}{z} \right), \quad z \in \mathbb{T} \end{equation} Notice the solution of this equation is simple, it is \begin{equation} \psi(z) = \begin{cases} bz/2 & |z| < 1 \\ b/2z & |z| > 1 \end{cases} \end{equation}

In [29]:
function psi(z;b=1)
    if abs(z)<1
        return b*z/2
    elseif abs(z)>1
        return b/(2*z)
    else
        return 0
    end
end
Out[29]:
psi (generic function with 1 method)
In [30]:
phaseplot(-2..2, -2..2, z -> psi(z), title="ψ(z)", xlabel="Re(z)", ylabel="Im(z)")
Out[30]:

It remains for us to invert from $\psi(z)$ back to $\phi(x)$. I claim that the following function is our desired solution (before scaling back) \begin{equation} \phi(x) = \frac{\psi(J_+^{-1}(x)) + \psi(J_-^{-1}(x))}{2} \end{equation} To show this we note that along $x \in [-1,1]$, \begin{gather*} \psi^+(J_+^{-1}(x)) = \psi^+(J_D^{-1}(x))\\ \psi^-(J_+^{-1}(x)) = \psi^-(J_U^{-1}(x))\\ \psi^+(J_-^{-1}(x)) = \psi^+(J_U^{-1}(x))\\ \psi^-(J_-^{-1}(x)) = \psi^-(J_D^{-1}(x)) \end{gather*} AND \begin{gather*} \psi^+(J_U^{-1}(x)) + \psi^-(J_U^{-1}(x)) = \psi^+(J_D^{-1}(x)) + \psi^-(J_D^{-1}(x)) = bx \end{gather*} Combining we have \begin{equation*} \phi^+(x) + \phi^-(x) = bx \end{equation*}

We are not done yet -- we have not checked the decaying properties $\phi(x)$. We first simplify $\phi(x)$ by noting that $\psi(J_+^{-1}(x)) = b J_+^{-1}(x)/2$ and $\psi(J_-^{-1}(x)) = b (J_-^{-1}(x))^{-1}/2 = b J_+^{-1}(x)/2$. Therefore we have \begin{equation} \phi(x) = \frac{b}{2}\left(x - \sqrt{x-1}\sqrt{x+1} \right) = \frac{bx}{2}\left(1 - \sqrt{1-\frac{1}{x}}\sqrt{1+\frac{1}{x}} \right) \end{equation} Rescaling back by $x \to x/b$ yields \begin{equation} \phi(x) = \frac{x}{2}\left(1 - \sqrt{1-\frac{b}{x}}\sqrt{1+\frac{b}{x}} \right) = \frac{b^2}{4} \frac{1}{x} + ... \end{equation} For $\phi(x)$ to satisfy the decaying property we need $b^2/4 = 1$, or $b = 2$. Therefore the equilibrium measure has support $[-2,2]$ and its density has Cauchy transform \begin{equation} \phi(x) = \frac{x}{2}\left(1 - \sqrt{1-\frac{2}{x}}\sqrt{1+\frac{2}{x}} \right) = \frac{1}{2}\left(x - \sqrt{x-2} \sqrt{x+2} \right) \end{equation}

To obtain the final density $w(x)$ we utilise Plemelj I and notice that when $x \in [-2,2]$, we have \begin{align*} \left(\sqrt{x^2-4}\right)_+ - \left(\sqrt{x^2-4}\right)_- &= \sqrt{x+2} \left(\sqrt{x+2}\right)_+ - \left(\sqrt{x+2}\right)_- \\ &= 2i\sqrt{4-x^2} \end{align*} Therefore \begin{equation} w(x) = \frac{i}{2\pi} \left(\phi^+ - \phi^- \right) = \frac{1}{2\pi} \sqrt{4-x^2} \end{equation} which is the semicircle law :)

In [31]:

# equilibriummeasure(x -> x, 0..1; bounded=:right)

plot!(x -> sqrt(4-x^2)/(2*pi), -2, 2)

Onto the Numerics¶

One may wonder if we generalise the above calculation to any convex potential $V(x)$ with only one minimum. We assume that the equilibrium measure has support $(a,b)$. Let $V'(x) = f$. We would like to solve \begin{align*} \phi^+(z) + \phi^-(z) &= f, \quad z \in (a,b) \\ \phi(z) &= \int \frac{w(x)}{z-x} = \frac{2\pi}{i} \mathcal{C}_\gamma[w](z) \sim O(z^{-1}) \end{align*}

One should note a simplification: there is a bijective map from $(a,b)$ to $(-1,1)$: \begin{equation} M_{(a,b)}(x) = \frac{2x-(a+b)}{b-a} \end{equation} Therefore if $\phi$ satisfies $\phi^+ + \phi^- = f$ for $z \in (a,b)$ then the function $\tilde{\phi}(x) = \phi(M_{(a,b)}^{-1}(x))$ satisfies \begin{equation*} \tilde{\phi}^+(x) + \tilde{\phi}^-(x) = f(M_{(a,b)}^{-1}(x)) := \tilde{f}(x), \quad z \in (-1,1) \end{equation*} Of course, if we define $\psi(z) = \tilde{\phi}(J(z))$ then we must have \begin{equation*} \psi^+(z) + \psi^-(z) = \tilde{f}(J(z)), \quad z \in \mathbb{T} \end{equation*}

Magic happens when we can write $\tilde{f}(x)$ in Chebyshev expansion, i.e. \begin{equation} \tilde{f}(x) = \sum_{k=0}^\infty \hat{f}_{k} T_k(x) \end{equation} (here $\hat{f}_k$ depends on $a$ and $b$!). Then \begin{equation} \tilde{f}(J(e^{i\theta})) = \hat{f}_0 + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=-\infty}^\infty \hat{f}_{|k|} e^{i k\theta} \end{equation} In other words, for all $z \in \mathbb{T}$, we have \begin{equation} \tilde{f}(J(z)) = \hat{f}_0 + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=-\infty}^\infty \hat{f}_{|k|} z^k \end{equation} Remark: $\hat{f}_{|k|}$ is the Fourier coefficients of $\tilde{f}(J(e^{i\theta})$), and you can estimate those by (Fast) Fourier Transform.

Again, if we define \begin{equation*} F^+(z) = \hat{f}_0 + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^\infty \hat{f}_{|k|} z^k, \quad F^-(z) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=-\infty}^{-1} \hat{f}_{|k|} z^k \end{equation*} Then the function \begin{equation*} \psi(z) = \tilde{\phi}(J(z)) = \begin{cases} F^+(z) & |z| < 1 \\ F^-(z) & |z| > 1 \end{cases} \end{equation*} satisfies $\psi^+(J(z)) + \psi^-(J(z)) = \tilde{f}(J(z))$. Using previous argument, we may then guess the following function \begin{align} \tilde{\phi}'(x) = \frac{\psi(J_+^{-1}(x)) + \psi(J_-^{-1}(x))}{2} \\ = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^\infty \hat{f_k} (J^{-1}_+(z))^k \end{align} satisfies \begin{align*} \tilde{\phi}'^+(x) + \tilde{\phi}'^-(x) = \tilde{f}(x), \quad z \in [-1,1] \end{align*} using the arguments above. Unfortunately $\tilde{\phi}'^+(\infty) = \hat{f_0}/2$ so $\tilde{\phi}'^+(\infty) = \hat{f_0}/2$ does not decay?! One can mitigate by subtracting a correction term \begin{equation*} \frac{x \hat{f}_0 + C}{2\sqrt{x+1}\sqrt{x-1}} \end{equation*} notice that the function $(\sqrt{z+1}\sqrt{z-1})^{-1}$ only jumps outside $[-1,1]$ so does not affect the jump condition but enable the solution to decay in rate $O(x^{-1})$. By recaling back by substituting $x$ with $M_{(a,b)}(x)$ we have the formula \begin{equation*} \small \phi(x) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k=0}^\infty \hat{f_k} (J^{-1}_+(M_{(a,b)}(x)))^k - \frac{M_{(a,b)}(x) \hat{f}_0 + C}{2\sqrt{M_{(a,b)}(x)+1}\sqrt{M_{(a,b)}(x)-1}} \end{equation*}

We are not finished yet, since we don't know what is $a$ and $b$. The decay behaviour for $\phi(x)$ will set up two equations for $a,b$. Firstly, we want $\hat{f}_0 = C = 0$ for $\phi(x)$ to be bounded. Secondly, notice by substituting the approximations: \begin{equation*} J^{-1}_+(x) = \frac{1}{2x} + ..., \quad M_{(a,b)}(x) = \frac{2x}{b-a} + ... \end{equation*} yields \begin{equation*} \small \phi(x) = \frac{1}{2} \hat{f}_1 \left( \frac{1}{2\left( \frac{2x}{b-a} \right)} \right) + ... = \frac{b-a}{8} \, \hat{f}_1 \frac{1}{x} + ... \end{equation*} Therefore we demand \begin{equation*} \frac{b-a}{8} \, \hat{f}_1 = 1 \end{equation*} We may then find $a,b$ by solving these two equations, typically by Newton-Raphson, then perform the above procedure to obtain $\phi(x)$. We may then use Plemenlj I to conclude \begin{equation} w(x) = \frac{\sqrt{1-M_{(a,b)(x)}}}{\pi} \sum_{k=1}^\infty \hat{f}_k U_{k-1}(M_{(a,b)}(x)) \end{equation}

Example: Consider the potential $V(x) = e^x - x$ with $f(x) = V'(x) = e^x - 1$. Assume the equilibrium measure has support $(a,b)$. Then $$\tilde{f}(x) = \exp\left(\frac{1}{2} \left((b-a)x + (b+a) \right)\right) - 1$$ We solve for $a$ and $b$

In [202]:
function need_to_solve!(interval)
    a = interval[1]
    b = interval[2]
    f0 = Fun(x -> exp(x)-1, Chebyshev(Interval(a,b))).coefficients[1]
    f1 = Fun(x -> exp(x)-1, Chebyshev(Interval(a,b))).coefficients[2]
    return [f0,f1*(b-a)/8-1]
end

Let's compare with the official example. (See Sheehan Olver's EquilibriumMeasure.jl at https://github.com/JuliaApproximation/EquilibriumMeasures.jl ). You need to import the package via url.

Out[199]:

Discrepancy arises since I have only used the first 20 coefficients. One can go further to increase efficiency. Other than that, the shape of the density is similar.

We can generalise the method to some other functions, and possibly predict some GUE with non-Gaussian entries and explore universality of GUE. However, the scaling will be different. One can obtain an empirical scaling by looking at how the maximum eigenvalues increase as $n$ increases. This is a further direction to this project.
